    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-09T06:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-09T06:10:00-05:00" n="732"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11047: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief, U. S. Asiatic Fleet</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Yarnell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="10" xml:id="d732fn10">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Navy Department.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-09T19:10:00+08:00"
                            >November 9, 1937—7:10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0009. Letter from Admiral Hasegawa received today same subject my cipher 4th [<hi
                        rend="italic">5th</hi>] this month. In substance following: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>I have honor forward you reply of Commander Imperial Japanese Army forces
                            regarding question use of Soochow Creek which you and Admiral Little
                            brought up on board His Majesty’s Ship <hi rend="italic">Idzumo</hi> 4
                            November; Army believes section this creek passing through and bounded
                            both sides by International Settlement is no part thereof. In view of
                            this, we consider have right navigate this waterway whenever in our
                            opinion considered necessary.</p>
                        <p>In cases where Nippon Army uses subject stream Navy may cooperate.
                            Recommend that since Chinese were denied use above river in Sector Baker
                            for military purposes State Department protest against its use in same
                            area by Japs as violation neutrality we have been observing toward each
                            of contending forces.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
